column1: Site-mapping of In Vitro S-nitrosation in the cardiac mitochondrial: Implications for cardioprotection.
column12: PRIDE ID: 13104. Published in Mol Cell Proteomics. 2010 ([[http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/21036925 PubMed]]). From the Abstract: {{i}}... a comprehensive assessment of mitochondrial SNO-modifiable cysteines was performed to determine nitric oxide (NO) susceptible pathways and identify novel mechanisms of oxidative cardioprotection. The biotin switch assay and mass spectrometry were used on rat cardiac mitochondrial lysates treated with the nitric oxide donor, S-nitrosoglutathione, and controls (n=3) to map 83 SNO-modified cysteine residues on 60 proteins. Of these, 3 sites have been reported, 30 sites are new to 21 proteins previously known to be S-nitrosated but which lacked site-specific information and 50 sites were found on 39 proteins not previously implicated. ...{{/i}}. Unmodified cysteines are presumed to have been S-NO modified {{i}}in vivo{{/i}}.

column12: Data obtained from the [[http://www.marcottelab.org/MSdata/Data_12/ authors website]]. Data file: 20090116_SMPA14_1.RAW. From the website: {{i}}Bacterial strains and growth. Pseudomonas aeruginosa UCBPP-PA14 was grown in Synthetic Cystic Fibrosis sputum medium (SCFM), which mimics the nutritional environment of the cystic fibrosis lung and has been previously described (Palmer, 2007). Bacterial growth in liquid media was monitored by measuring the optical density at 600 nm (OD600) during growth at 37with shaking at 250 rpm,m and cells were harvested at an OD600 of 0.4 to 0.5. We performed two biological replications for each experiment. Proteomics experiments. We harvested P. aeruginosa UCBPP-PA14 under the same conditions as described above. After cell lysis with a French press, we spun down cell debris twice (10,000 rpm, 20 min, 4, then removed the supernatant (soluble lysates).{{/i}}

column1: Shotgun proteomics on the osteocytic cell line MLO-Y4
column11: Nicoletta Bivi, Paola Picotti, Lukas N. Mueller, Milena Romanello, Luigi Moro, Franco Quadrifoglio and Gianluca Tell
column12: TRANCHE KEY: bPIBUscVPfkwacbe/87BIjAsGSAZWKH85BzW441WqsyUSwK/NqtfuI/DuXwfjA6gDoM+7qtkbAA72Q2sQmvykcq34s4AAAAAAAAFBA== Data file: OGE11. Shotgun proteomics on the osteocytic cell line MLO-Y4, to identify new targets of the anti-osteoporosis drugs Bisphosphonates. MLO-Y4 cells were treated with the Bisphosphonate Risedronate at the concentration 10-7M for 1h and 48h. At the end of the treatment protein extracts were prepared and analysed. The proteome at the basal, untreated condition was used as a reference to whom the proteome from stimulated cells was compared to.

column1: Identification of Phosphorylation Sites within the Signaling Adaptor APPL1 by Mass Spectrometry.
column12: TRANCHE KEY: ZEb8WJQd75/i4/POlusCyfWI7czMK+UT3kcIGy8P6caR3iYgUJdGR958BvUpwYS8v6Q56Pe1eiGKjK5H2Y8L/YG/A3kAAAAAAAAEDg== Gant-Branum, RL; Broussard, JA; Mahsut, A; Webb, DJ; McLean, JA.  J. Proteome Res.  2009, submitted. Human embryonic kidney (HEK) cells were transfected with FLAG-GFP-APPL1. After 36 h, cells were then incubated with 1 mM peroxovanadate and 50 nM calyculin A for 30 minutes and extracted. The lysates were precleared twice with mouse IgG-agarose and immunoprecipitated with FLAG-agarose (Sigma, St. Louis, MO) for 2 h at 4 degrees C. Samples were washed and FLAG tagged APPL1 was eluted by incubation of the beads with 0.2 mg/ml FLAG peptide in 25 mM Tris for 30 min at 4 degrees C. For MS analyses, APPL1 was separated into three equal aliquots and proteolytically digested by trypsin, chymotrypsin, and Glu C proteases, respectively. Proteolysis was quenched by adding 1 ul of neat formic acid. Subsequently, the digest was lyophilized and then reconstituted in 25 ul 0.1% formic acid. LTQ trypsin sample.

column1: Shotgun proteomics on the osteocytic cell line MLO-Y4
column11: Nicoletta Bivi, Paola Picotti, Lukas N. Mueller, Milena Romanello, Luigi Moro, Franco Quadrifoglio and Gianluca Tell
column12: TRANCHE KEY: bPIBUscVPfkwacbe/87BIjAsGSAZWKH85BzW441WqsyUSwK/NqtfuI/DuXwfjA6gDoM+7qtkbAA72Q2sQmvykcq34s4AAAAAAAAFBA== Data file: B06-9338_O48H3_c. Shotgun proteomics on the osteocytic cell line MLO-Y4, to identify new targets of the anti-osteoporosis drugs Bisphosphonates. MLO-Y4 cells were treated with the Bisphosphonate Risedronate at the concentration 10-7M for 1h and 48h. At the end of the treatment protein extracts were prepared and analysed. The proteome at the basal, untreated condition was used as a reference to whom the proteome from stimulated cells was compared to.

column1: Improved protein assembly with high discrimination peptide identification filtering.
column12: TRANCHE KEY: YWBO1ZyYI+iVHh2TuYyv9jEOFbb4t4s5KKMABO12ui3BDStQt1/+9W/o3Wj2q1z+ziah9DDcMjZ3qaddV1hMgHvcrbwAAAAAAAAGZA== The files in directory were generated from human colon adenocarcinoma cells (DLD-1 cell line) by Patrick Halvey of the Ayers Institute at Vanderbilt University.  Proteins were reduced and alkylated using iodoacetamide.  Peptides were produced through trypsin digestion, and the 90-minute RPLC separations (including a one hour shallow gradient) were conducted on an LTQ-XL at the Ayers Institute.  Five centroided tandem mass spectra were collected following each MS scan. These data are described more thoroughly in the following: Ma, ZQ; Dasari, S; Chambers MC; Litton, MD;  Sobecki, SM; Zimmerman, LJ; Halvey, PJ; Schilling, B; Drake, PM; Gibson, BW; Tabb, DL.  IDPicker 2.0: Improved protein assembly with high discrimination peptide identification filtering.  J. Proteome Res. 2009, in press. Collection of these data was supported by U24 CA126479.

column1: Shotgun proteomics on the osteocytic cell line MLO-Y4
column11: Nicoletta Bivi, Paola Picotti, Lukas N. Mueller, Milena Romanello, Luigi Moro, Franco Quadrifoglio and Gianluca Tell
column12: TRANCHE KEY: bPIBUscVPfkwacbe/87BIjAsGSAZWKH85BzW441WqsyUSwK/NqtfuI/DuXwfjA6gDoM+7qtkbAA72Q2sQmvykcq34s4AAAAAAAAFBA== Data file: OGE15. Shotgun proteomics on the osteocytic cell line MLO-Y4, to identify new targets of the anti-osteoporosis drugs Bisphosphonates. MLO-Y4 cells were treated with the Bisphosphonate Risedronate at the concentration 10-7M for 1h and 48h. At the end of the treatment protein extracts were prepared and analysed. The proteome at the basal, untreated condition was used as a reference to whom the proteome from stimulated cells was compared to.
